ce:section.ce:para:
The morphology, element composition and distribution of the photocatalyst were analyzed by scanning electron microscopy (Fig. 1

                     ) and EDS mapping (Fig. 2
                     ). As shown in Fig. 1, the surface of BCN was smooth and presented as aggregated blocks, which was consistent with previous findings [49]. The hexagonal rod-like structure of h-MoO3 was also consistent with that reported in the literature [42], indicating that the experiment successfully synthesized a hexagonal molybdenum trioxide material with good photocatalytic activity. In addition, it can also be clearly seen that h-MoO3 and g-C3N4 are not tightly combined in the material obtained by the heterojunction composite method (1), which can also be assembled with the results of the photodegradation experiment. In the MOCN compounded after ethanol mixing and ultrasonication, g-C3N4 is obviously peeled off and presents a layered structure, and h-MoO3 is also successfully compounded. When CDs were used to further modify the g-C3N4/h-MoO3 heterojunction material, the surfaces of g-C3N4 and h-MoO3 both appeared porous, which increased the active sites of electrons in the photocatalytic reaction. From the EDS mapping diagram of the 1CMOCN-3 photocatalyst (Fig. 2), C and N are uniformly distributed. Mo and O mainly exist in the h-MoO3 in the heterojunction, and the scattered Mo on the surface may be due to the partial destruction of h-MoO3 during the preparation of the heterojunction. In addition to the partially destroyed h-MoO3 dispersion, the O on the surface may also come from the adsorbed oxygen on the surface of the material.
